\begin{abstract}
Generic large language models (LLMs) regularly misstate domain definitions that are essential to physics analysis---event weights, missing-data conventions, and competition metrics---because they lack access to the project-local documents that fix those definitions. We describe \textbf{RAG AI Scientist}, a retrieval-augmented assistant for scientific repositories that indexes a project's PDFs and notes into a persistent Chroma vector store and exposes tool-style access to coding agents (in particular the Model Context Protocol in editors such as Cursor). Our primary contribution is a \textbf{transparent evaluation protocol} for that assistant---hand-authored queries with path-pattern relevance labels, optional lexical or RAGAS-style LLM-judge grounding scores, aggregate and stratified retrieval metrics, and explicit failure-case reporting. We complement retrieval with an \textbf{execution-grounded} axis: Oracle-Guided Tree Search (OGTS), a 50-task suite of domain-specific micro-tasks verified by deterministic oracles, which exposes systematic code-generation failures invisible to retrieval metrics. As a \textbf{validation testbed} we replicate the publicly documented 2014 ATLAS Higgs Boson Machine Learning Challenge: Monte Carlo weighting, sentinel missingness, weighted gradient boosting, and Approximate Median Significance. The replication reaches validation ROC-AUC \(\approx 0.92\) and weighted accuracy \(\approx 0.998\) on in-sample diagnostic curves after stratified K-fold estimation, matching the methodology of the challenge brief and demonstrating why the \textbf{same documents} the assistant retrieves must actually be indexed for grounded answers. All artifacts (eval JSON, figures, LaTeX source) are regenerated by a single pipeline (\texttt{run\_neurips\_pipeline.py}).
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

Scientific ML projects carry a rich local context: papers, challenge briefs, methodology notes, and configuration that define what a correct analysis looks like. Generic chat assistants frequently contradict that context---for example by omitting Monte Carlo weights during training, hallucinating the regulator in the Approximate Median Significance (AMS) metric, or misreporting missingness conventions. \textbf{RAG AI Scientist} targets this gap by indexing project documents into a local vector database and surfacing them to an agent via standardized tools; answers become traceable to specific chunks, and scientific claims can be audited against the retrieved sources.

This manuscript makes four contributions. First, we describe the assistant at the user-visible contract (\S\ref{sec:system}). Second, we present an \textbf{evaluation protocol} (\S\ref{sec:eval}) that reports honest retrieval metrics, stratifies by question difficulty, and emits a \textbf{failure-case table} whenever coverage gaps exist---turning coverage problems into concrete, actionable signals for corpus maintenance rather than hiding them behind averages. Third, we use a replication of the \textbf{ATLAS Higgs Boson Machine Learning Challenge (2014)}~\cite{adam2015higgs,atlas2014higgs} as a validation testbed (\S\ref{sec:casestudy}), producing a weighted classifier whose metrics we report alongside the retrieval evaluation so reviewers can verify that indexed methodology and executable code agree. Fourth, we introduce \textbf{OGTS} (Oracle-Guided Tree Search, \S\ref{sec:ogts}), a 50-task execution-grounded evaluation where generated code is verified by deterministic oracles, exposing systematic code-generation failures that retrieval metrics cannot detect.

\section{RAG AI Scientist}\label{sec:system}

\paragraph{Knowledge layer.}
The package (\texttt{rag-ai-scientist}) reads a YAML manifest of reference paths, extracts text from PDFs with \texttt{pymupdf4llm}, and indexes chunks into Chroma using a configurable embedding model (defaults in this repository mirror the HuggingFace \texttt{sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2} checkpoint with normalized vectors). For controlled comparisons across embedding families, we also ship \texttt{evals/run\_embedding\_sweep.py}, which rebuilds parallel persist directories under \texttt{.cursor/rag\_db\_\_<model>/} from the same \texttt{configs/references.yaml} chunking settings. The MCP server loads the resulting collection at runtime and exposes three retrieval tools (\texttt{query\_analysis\_knowledge}, \texttt{retrieve\_documents}, \texttt{search\_papers}) plus a skill-registry tool (\texttt{get\_skill}). If no cloud LLM key is configured, \texttt{query\_analysis\_knowledge} falls back to an extractive summary so that answers remain anchored to text that is physically present in the corpus.

\paragraph{Agent integration.}
Cursor (or any MCP-aware client) spawns the server via the standard stdio protocol, allowing the agent to issue tool calls during authoring, code review, or analysis. Skills under \texttt{.cursor/skills/} further constrain agent behavior to project conventions---a lightweight orthogonal mechanism to retrieval that nevertheless interacts with it (skills can direct the agent to consult specific indexed documents).

\paragraph{Scope of this draft.}
A full architectural description (chunking heuristics, embedding choices, provenance propagation) is outside the page budget here; our emphasis is on the \textbf{evaluation contract}, which is what lets downstream users trust this kind of assistant.

\section{Evaluation methodology}\label{sec:eval}

We evaluate \textbf{RAG AI Scientist} along three complementary axes: (i) \textbf{retrieval quality} against hand-labeled relevance (automatic); (ii) lightweight \textbf{answer grounding checks}---either cheap lexical presence tests (optional) or, when enabled, \textbf{RAGAS-style} faithfulness/context-relevance scores via an LLM judge; and (iii) \textbf{human rubrics} for qualitative claims. All runnable artifacts live in \texttt{evals/} in the repository.

\subsection{Gold queries and relevance}
The repository ships a small starter set in \texttt{evals/data/rag\_queries.jsonl}. For larger paper tables (e.g.\ $N{=}500$ with easy/medium/hard stratification), we also generate \texttt{evals/data/rag\_queries\_500\_neurips\_mirror.jsonl} via \texttt{evals/generate\_rag\_queries.py} (deterministic, reproducible).

Each JSONL line carries a \texttt{query} string, \texttt{relevant\_path\_patterns} (substrings that must appear in chunk metadata paths for the chunk to count as \emph{relevant}), optional \texttt{required\_terms} for lexical grounding, and a \texttt{difficulty} tag. Pattern matching proxies ``correct document family'' when chunk identifiers are unstable between re-ingests.

\subsection{Metrics}
\textbf{Recall@$k$}: per query, 1 if any of the top-$k$ retrieved chunks is relevant, else 0; report the mean over queries.
\textbf{MRR}: mean reciprocal rank of the first relevant chunk (0 if none in the retrieved list).
\textbf{nDCG@$k$}: binary relevance per rank with logarithmic discount.
\textbf{Lexical groundedness (optional)}: for queries with \texttt{required\_terms}, fraction of queries whose tokens all appear in the concatenated top-$k$ chunk text (necessary, not sufficient).
\textbf{Faithfulness / context relevance (optional)}: when \texttt{--ragas} is enabled, we score an extractive answer built from the retrieved top-$k$ contexts using RAGAS metrics (requires extra dependencies and LLM credentials).
\textbf{Failure cases}: queries with gold labels that return \emph{no} relevant chunk within the retrieval depth, reported explicitly so coverage gaps are not hidden by averages.

\subsection{Implementation}
Evaluations execute via \texttt{evals/run\_retrieval\_eval.py} (library: \texttt{evals/retrieval\_eval\_lib.py}), loading the Chroma persist directory and embedding checkpoint used in production (\texttt{--embedding-model} must match the index). Gold data defaults to \texttt{evals/data/rag\_queries.jsonl}; pass \texttt{--queries} to evaluate alternate JSONL sets (including the 500-query mirror file). Optional RAGAS scores are enabled with \texttt{--ragas} after installing \texttt{evals/requirements-ragas.txt} and configuring a judge provider (see \texttt{evals/judge\_metrics.py}).

