\section{Case study: ATLAS Higgs Challenge replication}\label{sec:casestudy}

The 2014 ATLAS Higgs Boson Machine Learning Challenge~\cite{adam2015higgs,atlas2014higgs} asked participants to separate simulated Higgs-boson signal (label \texttt{s}) from background (\texttt{b}) using per-event Monte Carlo weights and a domain-specific metric, the Approximate Median Significance (AMS) with regulator $b_r=10$. Missing values are encoded as the sentinel $-999$. We replicate the training pipeline as a validation testbed for RAG AI Scientist: the same PDFs the assistant indexes must be consistent with executable code.

\paragraph{Pipeline.}
\texttt{run\_atlas\_pipeline.py} (i) filters rows with \texttt{KaggleSet} $=t$, (ii) maps $-999$ to NaN, (iii) runs \textbf{stratified 5-fold} cross-validation on \texttt{Label} with \texttt{sample\_weight}~$=$~\texttt{Weight}, fitting a \texttt{HistGradientBoostingClassifier}~\cite{scikitlearn} per fold and scanning the probability threshold to maximize AMS within each fold, (iv) reports fold-wise metrics summarized as mean$\pm$std, and (v) refits on the full training table for diagnostic ROC/AMS curves. Figures \ref{fig:mmc}--\ref{fig:importance} illustrate the class separation and classifier behavior.

