\section{Limitations}
\paragraph{Retrieval evaluation.} Path-pattern relevance is a \emph{proxy}; upgrading to stable chunk IDs improves precision when ingestion is frozen. Lexical groundedness only detects the \emph{presence} of required tokens, not their correct use; LLM-judge scores (when enabled) are closer to semantic faithfulness but introduce evaluator variance and cost. Metrics transfer only to the corpus version and embedding checkpoint reported alongside the JSON artifact.

\paragraph{Case study.} Validation AMS is \emph{not} the private leaderboard score~\cite{adam2015higgs}; we use it to anchor reproducibility, not to claim competitive ranking. Stratified K-fold cross-validation (reported as mean$\pm$std) reduces sensitivity to a single random split, though it still does not substitute for the held-out competition test set.

\paragraph{OGTS.} The current 50-task suite covers only four families of scientific computing micro-tasks; broader coverage (tensor manipulation, data wrangling, plotting) would strengthen generalizability claims. The OGTS refinement prompt currently conveys only the oracle's pass/fail status---not the specific test-case failures---which limits tree-search recovery. Results are reported for a single model (\texttt{gpt-4o-mini}); scaling to larger or specialized code models is likely to change the pass-rate landscape and the relative advantage of OGTS over linear retry.

\section{Reproducibility}\label{sec:repro}

\paragraph{Build the index (one-off).}
\begin{verbatim}
rag-ai-scientist setup-rag \
  --project-root ~/Desktop/higgs \
  --collection-name higgs-rag --force
\end{verbatim}
This uses \texttt{configs/references.yaml}, which points at \texttt{references/}, \texttt{docs/}, and top-level \texttt{README.md}, so ATLAS, CMS, and methodology documents all enter the collection.

\paragraph{Run the pipeline.}
\begin{verbatim}
python run_neurips_pipeline.py \
  --rag-db ~/Desktop/higgs/.cursor/rag_db \
  --collection higgs-rag
\end{verbatim}
(or split eval and paper rendering across environments via \texttt{--reuse-eval-json}).

\section{Execution-grounded evaluation: Oracle-Guided Tree Search}\label{sec:ogts}

Retrieval metrics measure whether the assistant can \emph{cite} relevant material; they do not measure whether the code it produces is \emph{correct}. We therefore complement the retrieval harness with an \textbf{execution-grounded axis} that evaluates LLM-generated Python modules against deterministic oracles, following the pass@$k$ paradigm of HumanEval~\cite{humaneval}.

\subsection{Task suite}
We construct $N{=}50$ micro-tasks spanning four domain-specific families: (i)~AMS closed-form ($n{=}14$), (ii)~weighted log-loss ($n{=}12$), (iii)~nDCG@$k$ with binary relevance ($n{=}12$), and (iv)~threshold scan for AMS ($n{=}12$). Each task defines an entrypoint signature, a natural-language prompt, and 6 pre-computed oracle test cases with numeric tolerances. Tasks are generated deterministically (\texttt{seed=1337}) and stored in \texttt{evals/ogts/data/ogts\_50\_tasks.jsonl}.

\subsection{Strategies}
\paragraph{Linear retry (pass@$k$).} Sample $k$ independent modules at temperature $T$; return the first module that passes all oracle cases.
\paragraph{OGTS.} Inspired by tree-structured exploration~\cite{yao2023tot} with execution feedback~\cite{chen2023codet}: at each of $d$ depth steps, draw $b$ independent samples; run every sample through the oracle; return the first passing sample; otherwise advance using the highest-scoring survivor as context for the next depth. OGTS trades serial depth for parallel width, letting the oracle prune bad branches immediately.

