\paragraph{Error taxonomy.} The nDCG family reveals a \emph{systematic} bug: \texttt{gpt-4o-mini} computes \texttt{log2(i+1)} with 0-based~$i$ (yielding \texttt{log2(1)=0} at rank~1, a division by zero or off-by-one), whereas the oracle expects 1-based ranks (\texttt{log2(i+1)} for $i=1\ldots k$). Average scores on failed nDCG tasks are ${\approx}0.96$, confirming near-correct but systematically shifted outputs. This is precisely the kind of ``invisible hallucination'' that lexical grounding cannot detect but execution oracles expose immediately.

\paragraph{Implications.} On well-specified closed-form tasks (AMS, log-loss), even a small model achieves $100\%$ pass rate at $k{=}1$. Harder compositional tasks (threshold scan, nDCG) benefit from either more attempts or deeper search. The current OGTS implementation provides marginal gains over linear retry on this suite; we hypothesize that feeding \emph{oracle error details} (not just status strings) into the refinement prompt would improve tree-search recovery, and plan to test this with larger models.

\section{Conclusion}
We presented \textbf{RAG AI Scientist} alongside a public evaluation protocol and used an ATLAS Higgs-challenge replication as a validation testbed. The retrieval harness exposes corpus-coverage gaps rather than papering over them, so even a failing run produces a concrete failure-case table guiding corpus maintenance. The OGTS execution-grounded harness adds a complementary axis: 50 domain-specific micro-tasks with deterministic oracles, revealing systematic code-generation failures (e.g.\ off-by-one in nDCG ranking) that retrieval metrics alone cannot detect. Code, configuration, task suite, and this document regenerate from a single pipeline.

